Location: Neighborhood (Including areas of Proctor Ave, Rice HS, Hadley Rd, Joy Dr, Farrell St, and inbetween locations))
Observation Details: So happy I decided to go on a walk. While walking, I decided to pause and observe the large rising moon. At the same time, a flock of 16 geese appeared due east of me, heading towards Lake Champlain like all of the other flocks. It was 7:34 PM. I immediately noticed that in the second-to-last position of this flock’s left arm of the V was a goose of diminutive size and a noticeably faster wing beat. The overall cadence of the bird’s wings seemed like that of a large duck. Over the next 10-15 seconds as it approached, I got a better sense that its overall size was a bit larger than a mallard and that both the body size and wingspan were smaller than the Canada Geese. Hard to say how much faster its wingbeats were compared to the Canadas, but I would estimate 30% faster. As the goose approached to fly directly over me, it had a noticeably shorter neck and smaller head than the Canadas. The flock’s distance from the ground at this point was about 100ft - even with the tallest white pine trees near the flock. Very similar plumage pattern to Canadas. That said, due to the extremely bright moonlight rising while there was still enough dusk light to effectively see, I saw more white moonlight reflect off of the Canada Geese breast than that of the Cackling Goose, suggesting that the Cackling had a darker breast than the Canada Geese. As it continued on, it fell back to the last position in the V. This was the last flock that I observed this evening. The flight trajectory of this flock at the time of flyover suggested that it was heading towards the area of Red Rocks beach in Shelburne Bay. Amazing chance.
Checklist Comments: Decided to go on a walk after dinner because I heard so many flyover Canada Geese. Started 7:13, ended 7:45. Last flyover was 7:34 which included the Cackling Goose. 71F, clear skies, evening dusk with large, bright rising moon.

Observation Details: Saw flying away. Could not identify in the field due to distance and lighting. I did note how it had a small purple patch on the top side of the wing that was at the base of the wing near the body - smaller than one would expect on a mallard. Additionally, I noticed a white band at the end of this color patch along the edge of the wing and did not see one on the inner side of the color patch. Beyond that, the duck appeared uniformly gray. Upon research at home, I realized that I saw a female wood duck.

Observation Details: Flying northward low in the sky relative to other hawks in migration. Difficult to estimate distance from the ground, but it was close enough to see its plumage pattern with bare eyes - perhaps 500m. Flight style was mostly slow active flapping (one flap every 1-3 seconds) but did observe some soaring in a thermal. It had a slight wobble when gliding in between flaps. Underside (body, wings, and tail) was very white and pale with distinct black wingtips. Light gray head. Must've been a male.

Location: Dead Creek WMA IBA--Stone Bridge Dam

Observation Details: One merlin perched high in a tree along a strip of trees nestled between two fields. This merlin gave out repeated calls for about 1 minute. It was small, similar in size to a kestrel but with a gray/ bluish back and mottled front. Then, this merlin took off from the tree and exhibited 5-10 very rapid wingbeats followed by a short glide, then another set of rapid wingbeats before perching on another tree. At this time, a second merlin took off from a location near to where the first one originated and exhibited identical flight behavior before perching close to the other merlin. At this time, a mixed flock of songbirds (ID-ed in this checklist) that was about 50 meters from the perched merlins began to exhibit significantly louder behavior. This is backed up with a second recording identified as such by the namesake Merlin application.

Location: Sugarbush Resort trail to the top, Warren US-VT (44.1325,-72.9072)

Observation Details: My fourth sighting of this Merlin in the past week in my residential backyard, and it’s now clear that it’s the taiga subspecies. Long tail when in flight, dark outer feathers with very white under tail and vent feathers. Exterior wing feathers are gray. White chest feathers with speckled brown. Gray head with white streaks. Flies with rapid wingbeats, and swoops down a few feet while already in lateral flight movement to hunt (possible targeting a black-capped chickadee). Wingspan about 2 feet across. Flies low to the ground, from about 20 feet above to a mere 2 or 3 feet. Superb angling to avoid backyard objects and trees. Have seen it perch on tree branches for no more than 2 minutes before flying away.
Soared right over head at lower end of lake trail
